spi: drain the queues in the worker (fixes lost transactions)

The SPI worker serviced exactly ONE transaction per invocation, while
queue_work() calls coalesce whenever a run is already pending. Under
bursts (multi-frame scan results, command sequences) the worker gets
fewer invocations than there are transactions; a queued TX then waits
for a handshake EDGE that never comes, because the line is already
high. Field signature on the F1C200s: first scan returns fine, second
command times out forever with handshake high / data-ready low and the
frame still in the queue; adding printk delays (heisenbug-style) made
it disappear. Raspberry Pi hosts mask the race with different timing.

Loop until there is nothing to send, nothing pending from the ESP, or
the ESP deasserts ready. Validated on hardware: five consecutive scans
(16-17 SSIDs) with zero timeouts, and cfg80211 AP mode (hostapd)
reaches AP-ENABLED -- previously both died on the second exchange.

Signed-off-by: mbt28 <btekbas@gmail.com>

--- a/esp_hosted_ng/host/spi/esp_spi.c
+++ b/esp_hosted_ng/host/spi/esp_spi.c
@@ -293,6 +293,7 @@
 	int ret = 0;
 	volatile int trans_ready, rx_pending;
 
+next_transaction:
 	trans_ready = gpio_get_value(HANDSHAKE_PIN);
 	rx_pending = gpio_get_value(SPI_DATA_READY_PIN);
 
@@ -390,6 +391,15 @@
 			dev_kfree_skb(rx_skb);
 
 		dev_kfree_skb(tx_skb);
+
+		/* Drain until idle: queue_work() calls coalesce while a run
+		 * is pending, so a single-shot worker loses transactions
+		 * under bursts -- a queued TX then waits for a handshake
+		 * EDGE that never comes (the line is already high). Loop
+		 * until there is nothing to do or the ESP is not ready. */
+		tx_skb = NULL;
+		rx_skb = NULL;
+		goto next_transaction;
 	}
 }
 
